Note that something like this is actually part of C99 (but not of C++ - the C++ grammar was apparently too tortured to support this):<p><pre><code>    struct example_t {
        int foo, bar, baz;
    } example = {
        .foo = 1,
        .bar = 42,
    };
    /* unnamed members are implicitly set to 0 / NULL */
    assert(example.baz == 0);
</code></pre>
combined with compound literals, you can do stuff like<p><pre><code>   example = (struct example_t){
      .foo = 2,
      .baz = 1
   };
   assert(example_cmp(&example,
      &(struct example_t){ .foo = 2 }) == 0);
</code></pre>
It&#x27;s one of C99&#x27;s neater features, I think. I can imagine C++ programmers liking something like iod.
